===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[Power]] or right to make or [[enforce]] rules or give orders; or a [[position]] having such power or right.
#: {{ux|en|I have the '''authority''' to penalise the staff in my department, but not the '''authority''' to sack them.}}
#: {{ux|en|Vigilantes may have the power to nab criminals, but they lack the '''authority'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|She lost all respect and '''authority''' after turning up drunk at the meeting.}}
#: {{ux|en|Respect my '''authority'''!}}
#* '''1777''', {{w|Richard Brinsley Sheridan}}, ''The School for Scandal'', II.i:
#*: SIR PETER. Very well! ma'am very well! so a husband is to have no influence, no '''authority'''?
#*: LADY TEAZLE. '''Authority'''! no, to be sure—if you wanted '''authority''' over me, you should have adopted me and not married me[:] I am sure you were old enough.
#* '''1883''', {{w|Howard Pyle}}, ''{{w|The Merry Adventures of Robin Hood}}'' [[s:The Merry Adventures of Robin Hood/Chapter V|Chapter V]]
#*: But in the meantime Robin Hood and his band lived quietly in Sherwood Forest, without showing their faces abroad, for Robin knew that it would not be wise for him to be seen in the neighborhood of Nottingham, those in '''authority''' being very wroth with him.
# {{lb|en|[[plural]]}} Persons, regarded [[collectively]], who occupy official positions of power; [[police]] or [[law enforcement]].
#: {{ux|en|'''Authorities''' say the suspect fled on foot.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1927|author=[http://openlibrary.org/authors/OL2416183A F. E. Penny]
|chapter=4|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL16814587W Pulling the Strings]
|passage=The case was that of a murder. It had an element of mystery about it, however, which was puzzling the '''authorities'''. A turban and loincloth soaked in blood had been found; also a staff.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-08-10|volume=408|issue=8848|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21583270-new-zealands-plan-regulate-designer-drugs-better-trying-ban-them-and-failing-new Legal highs: A new prescription]
|passage=No sooner has a [synthetic] drug been blacklisted than chemists adjust their recipe and start churning out a subtly different one. These &ldquo;legal highs&rdquo; are sold for the few months it takes the '''authorities''' to identify and ban them, and then the cycle begins again.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[reliable]], trustworthy source of information on a subject.
#: {{ux|en|the world's foremost '''authority''' on orangutans}}
#: {{ux|en|My cheap dictionary is not the '''authority''' on word derivations.}}
#* '''1930''' September 18, Albert Einstein, as quoted in ''Albert Einstein: Creator and Rebel'' (1988) by Banesh Hoffman
#*: To punish me for my contempt of authority, Fate has made me an '''authority''' myself.
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[Status]] as a trustworthy source of information, reputation for [[mastery]] or [[expertise]]; or claim to such status or reputation.
#: {{ux|en|Some thinkers regard appealing to '''authority''' as a logical fallacy; others regard it as a legitimate form of argument.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A government-owned [[agency]] that runs a revenue-generating activity for public benefit.
#: ''{{w|New York Port '''Authority'''}}''; ''{{w|Chicago Transit '''Authority'''}}''
# {{q|uncountable}} Official [[permission]]; [[authorization|authorisation]] to act in some [[capacity]] on behalf of a ruling entity.
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1964|month=July|title=XP64: New Standard Carriage Project|journal=Modern Railways|page=2|text='''Authority''' to construct eight carriages, to test the new design in public service, had already been given; but of course complete working drawings had first to be prepared.}}

